Yes, JSON-L (JSON Lines) format is where each line contains a complete, standalone JSON object. For assistant logs, each line typically includes:

```
{"timestamp":"2024-01-01T12:00:00Z","request_id":"abc-123","event_type":"tool_call","tool_name":"mcp__sequential-thinking__sequentialthinking","parameters":{...},"model":"claude-opus-4"}
{"timestamp":"2024-01-01T12:00:01Z","request_id":"abc-123","event_type":"tool_result","tool_name":"mcp__sequential-thinking__sequentialthinking","result":{...},"duration_ms":150}
{"timestamp":"2024-01-01T12:00:02Z","request_id":"abc-123","event_type":"message","role":"assistant","content":"...","token_count":{"input":1200,"output":350}}
```

Each line is independently parseable, making it ideal for streaming, grep operations, and log aggregation systems.

